{0 Doc dependency graphs and per-step closures}

Reference for {b which dependency closure each step of the doc
pipeline consumes.} The two-graph distinction (build_deps vs
doc_deps) and the four step kinds (build, doc compile, doc link,
doc-all) are easy to confuse. This page is the source of truth;
functions in the doc pipeline cite specific sections of this page
in their docstrings.

{1 Two dependency graphs}

The solver emits {!Day11_solution.Solve_result.t} containing two
related graphs over the same package set:

{ul
{- [build_deps] — what each package needs at {b build time}.
   {b Acyclic.} Excludes [{post}] deps because [{post}] deps are
   installed {e after} the package builds, not before. Used for
   build-DAG topological ordering.}
{- [doc_deps] — what each package's docs need at {b link time}.
   Equals [build_deps ∪ {post} ∪ x-extra-doc-deps].
   {b May contain cycles} (e.g. compiler ↔ ocaml virtual). Do not
   topologically sort. Used for odoc cross-reference resolution.}
}

{!Day11_doc.Doc_deps.needs_separate_link} compares a single
package's direct entries in the two graphs. When they differ, the
package needs separate compile and link phases; when they agree,
the two phases can be fused into a single doc-all phase.

{1 The four step kinds}

{2 1. Build — the package's own dune/make/etc.}

The actual package compile + install. Not part of odoc; produces
the build layer that doc steps consume.

{ul
{- {b Inputs:} this package's source + transitive build_deps'
   build layers (binaries: [ocamlobjinfo], [.cma], [.cmti], etc.).}
{- {b Output:} build layer with installed package files.}
{- {b Closure walked:} [build_deps] transitively. Never doc_deps.}
{- {b Code:} {!Day11_opam_build.Build_layer.build}.}
}

{2 2. Doc compile — odoc compile (.cmti → .odoc)}

odoc reads each compiled interface and emits a [.odoc] file
containing the typed AST plus references to other packages' types.
Cross-package type references (e.g. [type t = Other_pkg.X.t]) are
recorded but not yet resolved.

{ul
{- {b Inputs:} this package's build layer + transitive build_deps'
   compile layers (other packages' [.odoc] files for any type the
   [.cmti] mentions).}
{- {b Output:} compile layer with [.odoc] files.}
{- {b Closure walked:} [build_deps] transitively. {b Must match
   what the OCaml compile saw} — adding doc-only edges here would
   introduce dependencies the [.cmti] doesn't reference.}
{- {b Code:} {!Day11_doc.Generate.compile_package},
   {!Day11_doc.Doc_build.compile}.}
{- {b Layer-assembly fn:}
   {!Day11_doc.Generate.find_dep_compile_layers}, which walks
   [node.deps] (= build_deps) transitively.}
}

{2 3. Doc link — odoc link (.odoc → .odocl + HTML)}

odoc resolves cross-references and produces final [.odocl] files
plus HTML. {b This is where docstring [\{!Foo.t\}] markup is
resolved.} References may target packages that the build itself
didn't see — e.g. compiler types reached only through a [{post}]
edge, or extras declared via [x-extra-doc-deps].

{ul
{- {b Inputs:} this package's compile layer + transitive doc_deps'
   compile layers.}
{- {b Output:} link layer with HTML, rendered into [html_dir].}
{- {b Closure walked:} [doc_deps] transitively. {b Must include
   [{post}] and [x-extra-doc-deps]} because xrefs are resolved
   here, not at compile.}
{- {b Code:} {!Day11_doc.Generate.link_package},
   {!Day11_doc.Doc_build.link}.}
{- {b Layer-assembly fn:} should walk [doc_dep_hashes]
   transitively from [node.hash]. The graph already incorporates
   [{post}] and [x-extra-doc-deps] edges by construction in the
   solver.}
}

{2 4. Doc-all — fused compile + link}

An optimisation for packages where [build_deps == doc_deps] (i.e.
no [{post}] deps and no [x-extra-doc-deps] beyond build deps).
A single container start does both phases.

{ul
{- {b Valid when:}
   [not (Day11_doc.Doc_deps.needs_separate_link result pkg)].}
{- {b Inputs and output:} same as compile, plus the link's HTML
   output mounted.}
{- {b Closure walked:} [build_deps] transitively. Equivalent to
   walking [doc_deps] by precondition.}
{- {b Code:} {!Day11_doc.Generate.doc_all_package},
   {!Day11_doc.Doc_build.doc_all}.}
{- {b Layer-assembly fn:}
   {!Day11_doc.Generate.find_dep_compile_layers} (same as compile —
   correct because closures are equal).}
}

{1 Layer-mount conventions}

Each doc step mounts two stacks of layers as overlayfs build_dirs:

{ul
{- {b Build deps' BUILD layers} — for binaries on PATH
   ([ocamlobjinfo], compiler binaries). Always walked transitively
   from [build_deps] regardless of step. Code:
   {!Day11_doc.Generate.find_build_deps_layers}.}
{- {b Doc deps' COMPILE layers} — for [.odoc] files. Compile and
   doc-all walk [build_deps]; link walks [doc_deps]. The shared
   table {!Day11_doc.Generate.t.build_to_doc_hash} maps each
   build_hash to either a compile_node hash (for split packages)
   or a doc_all_node hash (for merged packages).}
}

{1 How a missing edge looks}

If a doc step's layer assembly omits a dep that should be there,
odoc cannot find that dep's [.odoc] file at xref-resolution time.
The HTML renders the reference as an [xref-unresolved] span instead
of a live link. {b The build does not fail.}

Two distinct hazards:

{ul
{- {b Wrong closure walked.} Walking [build_deps] at link instead
   of [doc_deps] means [{post}] deps are missed. Walking only the
   direct [doc_deps] (no transitive expansion) means anything two
   hops away is missed.}
{- {b Silent layer drop.}
   {!Day11_doc.Generate.find_dep_compile_layers} skips deps whose
   compile layer is not [Layer.is_ok]. A layer that built but
   produced an empty output (e.g. a "compiler" package whose build
   didn't install [stdlib.cmti]) will pass [is_ok] but contribute
   nothing — so xrefs to its types still don't resolve.
   {!Day11_opam_build.Compiler_pkg.check_stdlib_installed} is the
   defence against this for the compiler case.}
}

The test-repo package {b stdlib_ref} (T06 in the testlab timeline)
is a single-package canary: its docstrings reference
[\{!Stdlib.Format.formatter\}] and [\{!Stdlib.out_channel\}], so
unresolved spans there mean the compiler's compile layer didn't
make it into the link inputs.

{1 Pitfalls when adding new code}

{ul
{- {b Don't reuse [find_dep_compile_layers] in link.} It walks
   build_deps. Link needs a doc_deps walker.}
{- {b Don't conflate "is a compiler package" with "produces a
   compile node".} A package gets a compile_node iff
   {!Day11_doc.Doc_build.is_ocaml_package} returns true (depends
   on [ocaml] OR is one of the named compilers). Packages that
   don't satisfy this never appear in [build_to_doc_hash], and
   transitive walks silently skip them.}
{- {b Don't expect the runtime to fail loudly} when a declared
   compile-layer dep is missing — the silent-drop in
   [find_dep_compile_layers] is a known hazard. Add an explicit
   warning if you change the code path.}
}
